WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:03.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:03.510 --> 00:00:22.040
[ Silence ]

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:23.840
&gt;&gt; On behalf of the
audience thank you.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:32.710
[ Applause ]

00:00:32.710 --> 00:00:36.000
&gt;&gt; And my first question
to you Jason is

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.510
when exactly did you sell
your soul to the devil?

00:00:38.510 --> 00:00:42.080
[ Laughter ]

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:43.380
Jason Robert Brown

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:47.120
&gt;&gt; The real question is
what did I get in exchange?

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:51.260
No, you know, I started, I started
playing, I begged my parents

00:00:51.260 --> 00:00:54.100
for a piano when I was 7 I think.

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:56.440
And I have no musicians in
my family that's not sort

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:58.530
of part of the family tree.

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:04.040
We have no artists anywhere or at
least no actual artists anywhere.

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:07.990 position:56%
And, but I said I wanted a piano and
my grandfather was sort of a hoarder

00:01:07.990 --> 00:01:10.350
and he had them in his basement
and he had an old upright

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:13.140
in his basement which they
sort of brushed up a little bit

00:01:13.140 --> 00:01:16.040
and one day I came into my
living room and there it was.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:18.750 position:56%
And so I sat down and started trying
to figure out how to play the thing

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:22.400 position:56%
from Star Wars or something that
was kind of, that was that you know,

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:25.260
what I always say is, I was
the second child and as anyone

00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:28.280 position:56%
who is a second child or especially
anyone who is the first child knows,

00:01:28.280 --> 00:01:30.840 position:56%
you know, that means all I'm trying
to do all the time is get attention.

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:34.970
And so, you know, I was working
from a very early age to make sure

00:01:34.970 --> 00:01:39.290
that people noticed me, so this
turned out to be the way to do it.

00:01:39.290 --> 00:01:41.350
&gt;&gt; Did you start piano
lessons then or you?

00:01:41.350 --> 00:01:42.650
Jason Robert Brown

00:01:42.650 --> 00:01:43.950
&gt;&gt; I did, but only in the
most sort of rudimentary way,

00:01:43.950 --> 00:01:46.510
because I wouldn't practice
because it wasn't gratifying.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:49.140
[ Laughter ]

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:54.910
Uh-huh. And so I you know, I
took lessons for 3 or 4 years

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:56.690
but I never got to
any particular level.

00:01:56.690 --> 00:01:59.580
I was sort of on you know the
John Brimhall book 3 and you know,

00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:01.910
it was sort of you know, everyone
rolling their eyes every week.

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:03.970
But while I while I was doing
that I was also writing songs

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:05.820
and I would sit and write
songs and play in my own sort

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:08.460
of crazy idiosyncratic
way and do that.

00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:10.880
So that I kind of then, my mother
was like well I'm not going

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:12.520
to keep paying for lessons if
you're never going to practice.

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:14.430
So I just kept playing
and playing and playing,

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:17.650
but I never was doing it
according to the books and I sort

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:20.970
of got self-taught as far as
theory and how to read charts

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:22.560
and chords and things like that.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:25.800
And then right when I was about
to graduate from high school,

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:27.660
my mother said well what is
it you're planning to do?

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:30.010 position:56%
I said, well I have to go to a music
school of course that's what I do.

00:02:30.010 --> 00:02:32.100
And she said, well it would help
if you could read music probably,

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:35.250
that would, that might be
valuable and we sort of shoved me

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:38.010
into piano lessons for the last
year of high school and I sort

00:02:38.010 --> 00:02:42.640
of crammed, how to figure out how
to integrate what I knew how to do

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.220
with what actually was on the page.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:46.400
And I'm still not sensational
with the page

00:02:46.400 --> 00:02:49.680
but I'm obviously a
lot better than I was.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:52.190
&gt;&gt; I think there are a lot of sort

00:02:52.190 --> 00:02:58.020 position:56%
of aspiring musical theater
performers and writers here and ones

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:00.830
who are beyond aspiring, but I.

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:02.130
Jason Robert Brown

00:03:02.130 --> 00:03:03.430
&gt;&gt; In both senses that way.

00:03:03.430 --> 00:03:06.040
&gt;&gt; In both senses of the word.

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:09.220
I'm just fascinated about
how you guys work together.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:12.780
I was able to watch a little
bit of your rehearsal before.

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:17.720
How do you evolve this
relationship and is there,

00:03:17.720 --> 00:03:20.260
it's sort of like there's almost
a psychic connection there

00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:23.960
of how you know reading each other

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:26.340
and how you're going
to work together.

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:27.660
Jason Robert Brown

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:31.030
&gt;&gt; I mean on my end,
really my belief is

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:34.450
that when you find the people
who connects to your material

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:36.210
and who you connect to musically,

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:38.460
the best thing you can do
is let them go do their job.

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:41.590
So, it's I don't sort of,
I don't think Shoshana

00:03:41.590 --> 00:03:43.480
and I have ever had a rehearsal
where we sit and I sort

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:45.440 position:56%
of micromanage the phrasing and sort

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:47.090
of say oh it should
be this and that.

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:49.040
Often what happens is
exactly what you saw today

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:52.030
where she's learned the song
from a recording that I send her

00:03:52.030 --> 00:03:54.980
or something like that and then we
have like 20 minutes before the gig

00:03:54.980 --> 00:03:56.280 position:56%
and I'm like all right let's try it.

00:03:56.280 --> 00:03:59.120
I might say one thing about oh,
no-no that's E flat not E natural

00:03:59.120 --> 00:04:03.820
and she'll be like ahh, that'll
be the entirety of our rehearsal.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:08.940
But, but it's, that's as much
as that's been the entirety

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:10.550
of our rehearsal, it's also one

00:04:10.550 --> 00:04:12.340
of my favorite collaborations
in my life.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.480
And whenever I can
sing with Shoshana I do

00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:16.920
because she just gets the material.

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:20.320
And so I don't have to say oh
no the phrase should go this way

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:23.460 position:56%
or what I meant for that, what
that's supposed to mean acting wise.

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:26.990 position:56%
She gets it, she does it, she brings
herself to it and then I can get

00:04:26.990 --> 00:04:29.720
out of the way, so
that's, that's my response.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:31.770
You? Shoshana Bean

00:04:31.770 --> 00:04:36.550 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I think, well it took me a number
of years to get out of the way

00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:39.230
and just let the, let
our connection be there

00:04:39.230 --> 00:04:41.360
and let the music does it for you.

00:04:41.360 --> 00:04:46.370 position:56%
But I was so terrified of him and so
wanting to please him and so wanting

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:51.470
to do his incredible music justice
that I think it was just kind

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:55.790
of not stale but just a little
stiff and terrifying for me.

00:04:55.790 --> 00:04:57.630
I don't know how it came across
but it was terrifying and then.

00:04:57.630 --> 00:04:59.100
&gt;&gt; Jason Robert Brown

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:00.900
&gt;&gt; You were fine huh?

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:06.040
[ Laughter &amp; Applause ]

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:07.340
Shoshana Bean

00:05:07.340 --> 00:05:09.210
&gt;&gt; The gift for me
is, it's very rare

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:10.980 position:56%
that you come across, thank you sir.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.280
Psychic connection.

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:14.030
You see how that works?

00:05:14.030 --> 00:05:19.020
That you as a singer or just an
artist in general with something

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:23.250
to say or feelings that you come
across someone who articulates them

00:05:23.250 --> 00:05:27.490
so perfectly and also writes so
perfectly for your instrument.

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:30.360
And I think a lot of women
say that about Jason's work.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:37.260
But me in particular, I feel like
myself in particular, It's just,

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:41.910
I think it's powerful connection to
his music and us together you know.

00:05:41.910 --> 00:05:45.360
So for me it was just
getting out of the way

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:47.630
and just letting the connection
be there and not be afraid of it.

00:05:47.630 --> 00:05:49.160
&gt;&gt; How do you set keys
and things like that

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:50.460
if you haven't rehearsed it?

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:51.760
Shoshana Bean

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:53.060
&gt;&gt; That's the magic of him.

00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:54.360
He just knows, I've never gone to
him and been like this is too high

00:05:54.360 --> 00:05:55.800
or this sits in a weird place.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:58.680
There are very few male
composers who know exactly

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:01.090
where to put music for women.

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:05.700
And for me, I mean the songs aren't
even technically challenging.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:08.120
I don't have to go through and
maneuver with my voice teacher

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:10.600
or anything like I do with
a lot of other composers

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:13.300
because they just fit
in my voice and a lot

00:06:13.300 --> 00:06:15.610
of women's voices so easily.

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:17.620
Every once and awhile
there's a murderess vowel

00:06:17.620 --> 00:06:20.760
or consonant on a murderess
note but.

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:22.060
Jason Robert Brown

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:23.360
&gt;&gt; Mine too.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:24.660
Shoshana Bean

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:25.960
&gt;&gt; And they're not easy.

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:29.190
They're challenging but I
love, it's like, it's a one,

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:32.510
I feel like this is the moment I
get to feel like an Olympic athlete

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:34.390
as a singer when I'm
approaching Jason's material.

00:06:34.390 --> 00:06:35.690
Jason Robert Brown

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:37.060
&gt;&gt; I mean part of that really
is, part of why Shoshana

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:41.460 position:56%
and I can do the work we do together
is that part of her voice happens

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:43.900
to be just the part of the
voice that I work in the most

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:45.200
and that I like the most.

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:47.550
So, it's not like oh maybe I'll
take this down a half step,

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:49.950
because Shoshana's singing it
which I will do with other signers.

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:52.090
But Shoshana it's been pretty
much whatever key I throw

00:06:52.090 --> 00:06:53.450
at her she's always like
oh that's good, that works.

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:54.750
Shoshana Bean

00:06:54.750 --> 00:06:56.050
&gt;&gt; Are you serious?!

00:06:56.050 --> 00:06:57.350
Jason Robert Brown

00:06:57.350 --> 00:06:58.970
&gt;&gt; Oh yeah.

00:06:58.970 --> 00:07:01.280
[ Laughter ]

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:02.740
Jason Robert Brown

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:04.040
&gt;&gt; No.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.940 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Do you do it from a recording, do
you provide the recording that she.

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:08.240
&gt;&gt; Jason Robert Brown

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:10.300
&gt;&gt; Well yeah, for the most
part, I mean you know,

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:11.910
we've now been doing these shows,

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:13.370
this has been more
than like 10 years.

00:07:13.370 --> 00:07:15.480
It's probably been 12 years of
doing these things together,

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:17.330
so I don't even remember
how we first.

00:07:17.330 --> 00:07:19.780
I think honestly when we first
did the gig you knew a lot

00:07:19.780 --> 00:07:21.820
of the songs already that you just
sort of showed up and you were

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:23.420
like I know Still Hurting
and I know how

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:25.270
to do I'd Give It All
for You, oh okay.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:26.660
Shoshana Bean

00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:29.430
&gt;&gt; No, I think you gave me, now
I don't remember the original,

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:31.460
I mean some of them I
had done in college.

00:07:31.460 --> 00:07:36.060
But now he just sends me, now
I'm known to ask for things.

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:37.980
&gt;&gt; Do you read music?

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:39.280
Shoshana Bean

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:40.580
&gt;&gt; I do, but I don't
need to with Jason.

00:07:40.580 --> 00:07:42.300
With Jason it's a feeling
thing and if there's a question

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:45.180
of a specific note, I
mean I just, I ask him.

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:46.480
I don't look at the music.

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:47.780
Jason Robert Brown

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:49.080
&gt;&gt; No, I mean with, with Cassandra

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:50.380
which tonight she did
for the first time.

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:53.710
I mean that's the first time that
anyone's done that song here.

00:07:53.710 --> 00:07:58.680
I sent her a recording of me
sort of, she had heard me do it.

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:01.230
We did a concert together in
London I guess, 2 months ago

00:08:01.230 --> 00:08:04.130
and I sang Cassandra then and I
said, but when we do the concert

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:06.960
in D.C. you're singing
it and she was like okay.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:09.350
And so, she had said you
better send it to me.

00:08:09.350 --> 00:08:12.490
So I sent her a recording where
I was playing the piano part

00:08:12.490 --> 00:08:14.170
and plunking out the
note at the same time

00:08:14.170 --> 00:08:15.880
and then I sent her
just an accompaniment

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:17.350
that she could sing along to.

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:19.850
And so I sent that I and I
again, today was the first time

00:08:19.850 --> 00:08:22.520
that we worked on it and you heard
you know, I started playing it,

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:24.410
she sang it and at the
end of it I said one thing

00:08:24.410 --> 00:08:25.710
about one phrase and she said okay.

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:28.160
And she was like okay let's
do it again and that was it.

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:30.120
&gt;&gt; That was one of the
most fascinating things

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:33.010
when you were doing sort
of the run through is

00:08:33.010 --> 00:08:37.450
as I recall you sang something
and then after you've gone

00:08:37.450 --> 00:08:41.320
through the song you said,
remember that phrase.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:45.790
She's not angry at him there,
she's genuinely wishing him well.

00:08:45.790 --> 00:08:47.090
Shoshana Bean

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:48.390
&gt;&gt; Did I do, did I do it tonight?

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:49.690
Jason Robert Brown

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:50.990
&gt;&gt; I wasn't paying attention.

00:08:50.990 --> 00:08:52.290
I was playing.

00:08:52.290 --> 00:08:53.590
[ Laughter ]

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:54.890
Shoshana Bean

00:08:54.890 --> 00:09:01.600
&gt;&gt; Mark, did I do it?

00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:02.900
Did I do it?

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:05.560
&gt;&gt; Everything you do is perfect.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:08.440
Shoshana Bean

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:13.460
&gt;&gt; I'm never leaving
the Library of Congress.

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:14.760
Isn't it great?

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:16.830
&gt;&gt; But it's fascinating
to me that the idea

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:19.890
of what an intension is
behind a song and a moment

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:25.340
versus what the singers bring
to it and I'm not even sure how

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:27.080
to articulate this question.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:28.380
Jason Robert Brown

00:09:28.380 --> 00:09:29.680
&gt;&gt; No, I think what
you're asking is this.

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:32.880
When you're a storyteller and I
think both of us are storytellers

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:34.180
as that's part of what we do.

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:37.010
It's much more effective for me
to tell you what the story is

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:41.540
that I need you tell than for me
to tell you how to tell that story.

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:44.730
If I had said to her, oh no do
it with this, go lighter on it

00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:46.450
and you know, it should be
more piano and maybe sort

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:50.160
of hang this one note over by an
extra eighth note, that may be sort

00:09:50.160 --> 00:09:52.110
of what I'm hoping comes out,

00:09:52.110 --> 00:09:53.840
but it doesn't mean
she'll understand the story

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:55.140
that I want to tell.

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:56.440
All I have to say to her is no
that's supposed to be genuine

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:57.740
and it's supposed to
be sort of kind.

00:09:57.740 --> 00:09:59.040
And by saying that I know
that she's going to interpret

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:00.340
that musically to mean something.

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:01.640
I don't know that with
every singer I work with

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:02.940
but I know that with Shoshana.

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:04.240
If I say something about what the
storytelling is supposed to be,

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:05.540
she knows how to tell stories with
the music as well as just sort

00:10:05.540 --> 00:10:06.840
of say the words, but the music
is going to tell a story also

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:08.140
and I can, you know I can trust
that, I can say that and it works.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:09.440
I hope.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:10.740
Shoshana Bean

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:12.040
&gt;&gt; I'm flattered.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:13.340
I nailed it tonight.

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:14.640
As you all can see, I nailed it.

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:15.940
[ Laughter ]

00:10:15.940 --> 00:10:18.720 position:56%
&gt;&gt; It interests me that most of what
you sang tonight are theater songs

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:21.880
and in a couple of cases you
sort of explicated the story,

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:23.420
especially with the new song.

00:10:23.420 --> 00:10:28.900
But so often it seemed unnecessary
and yet there's a lot of detail

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:32.460
that may not be clear to the
audiences but somehow the meaning

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:34.320
and understanding comes through.

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:35.620
Shoshana Bean

00:10:35.620 --> 00:10:37.280
&gt;&gt; That's because he's
a genius storyteller.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:41.280
He's a genius and this is the
other thing I say to highlight

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:45.210
that fact is as singers
who learn music,

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:47.630
I don't know if you notice some
of the songs are 5 minutes long

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:49.520
and there's a lot of words.

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:53.130
And so whenever, like when
I got Cassandra I was like

00:10:53.130 --> 00:10:56.050 position:56%
and I called Eden, because my friend
