00:22:55.360 --> 00:22:57.360
that kind of can sing along
with all of it and know it.

00:22:57.360 --> 00:22:58.660
And then another half of the crowd

00:22:58.660 --> 00:23:01.030
that really doesn't entirely
know what they're in for.

00:23:01.030 --> 00:23:03.410
And when there's that
balance it's a great thing

00:23:03.410 --> 00:23:06.230 position:56%
because you can feel the audience
sort of talk to each other you know,

00:23:06.230 --> 00:23:08.990
that they just share this thing
that it's all right to like it

00:23:08.990 --> 00:23:10.480
and it's all right to
be challenged by it

00:23:10.480 --> 00:23:11.780 position:56%
and it's all right to respond to it.

00:23:11.780 --> 00:23:13.550
Were all going to be fine.

00:23:13.550 --> 00:23:14.850
Whenever I have to
play for an audience

00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:18.080
that really doesn't know
anything about my work,

00:23:18.080 --> 00:23:21.500
that's a big uphill climb
because the material is so dense.

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:26.610
And a lot of it is so hard on you
know, first hearing that I have

00:23:26.610 --> 00:23:29.600
to be very careful about
how I program that set.

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:32.400
And I tend to do a lot of
jiggering around while I'm

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:33.700
in the middle of playing.

00:23:33.700 --> 00:23:35.570 position:56%
I'll be like oh I was going to do
this song, I'm not going to do that.

00:23:35.570 --> 00:23:36.870
Now let me just play.

00:23:36.870 --> 00:23:39.870
So I can respond to the energy
that way and feel that way,

00:23:39.870 --> 00:23:43.380
but so much of what I do with the
audience doesn't have to do with me

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:44.790
as a performer because I really,

00:23:44.790 --> 00:23:47.600
most of my time I don't spend
thinking about when I sing it.

00:23:47.600 --> 00:23:49.610
I spend most of my time thinking
about when the actor sings it,

00:23:49.610 --> 00:23:50.980
when the character sings it.

00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:54.310
So nights like this are sort
of fun, kicky little break.

00:23:54.310 --> 00:23:57.720
But most of the work is about
eliciting and audience response

00:23:57.720 --> 00:23:59.780
in a very specific way that's
built into the writing.

00:23:59.780 --> 00:24:01.190
So if I've done that right,

00:24:01.190 --> 00:24:05.110
hopefully when I perform
it, it's just sort of there.

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:08.660
&gt;&gt; What does it feel like having
sometimes say I Love Betsy is the

00:24:08.660 --> 00:24:10.660
best opening number
since the Music Man?

00:24:10.660 --> 00:24:11.960
Shoshana Bean

00:24:11.960 --> 00:24:13.260
&gt;&gt; What?!

00:24:13.260 --> 00:24:14.560
&gt;&gt; It did.

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:16.080
It's true.

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:18.300
[ Laughter ]

00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:19.760
Jason Robert Brown

00:24:19.760 --> 00:24:23.650 position:56%
&gt;&gt; It was, you know, it was awesome.

00:24:23.650 --> 00:24:24.950
The funny thing is, Honeymoon

00:24:24.950 --> 00:24:26.440
in Vegas was never the
show I thought was going

00:24:26.440 --> 00:24:27.740
to be Steve's cup of tea.

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:30.030
You know, I've known
Steve for a while

00:24:30.030 --> 00:24:33.110
and like any young
writer Steve, he's Steve.

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:34.750
I can call him Steve.

00:24:34.750 --> 00:24:38.310
But you know, like any young
writer of musical theater,

00:24:38.310 --> 00:24:40.890
all I ever wanted to do was
to get Steve to like me.

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:42.710
I was like Steve please
like my work.

00:24:42.710 --> 00:24:45.640
And so I think parade in the
last 5 years, those were the kind

00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:47.760
of shows I thought he's really
going to get behind those.

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:49.060
He's going to be into those.

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:53.250
And he was kind of like yeah
those are nice and then you know.

00:24:53.250 --> 00:24:57.690 position:56%
Honeymoon in Vegas which is so like
down the middle 1961 musical comedy,

00:24:57.690 --> 00:25:00.080
that's the one he's
like I love that show

00:25:00.080 --> 00:25:02.070
and that opening number is the
greatest thing I ever heard.

00:25:02.070 --> 00:25:05.630
He says, he told me that
he, he puts on the CD,

00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:08.320
he drives out to Connecticut to
his country house every weekend

00:25:08.320 --> 00:25:11.570
and he puts on I Love Betsy is the
first thing that he wants to listen

00:25:11.570 --> 00:25:13.910
to in the car and he just puts in
on repeat and he listens to it over

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:15.210
and over again and he cries.

00:25:15.210 --> 00:25:17.130
If anybody wants to know,
he cries all the time.

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:20.670
And, and I was like I Love Betsy?

00:25:20.670 --> 00:25:23.620
Really? That's the one?

00:25:23.620 --> 00:25:27.380
So I mean I'm grateful but,
that was, it was a surprise

00:25:27.380 --> 00:25:30.490 position:56%
that that was the one I mean I guess
he could've said Freaky Freaky,

00:25:30.490 --> 00:25:32.360
that would've been even
weirder but you know.

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:36.770
Still, I Love Betsy, okay great,
I mean I worked really hard on it.

00:25:36.770 --> 00:25:38.070
I'm glad it worked.

