00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:46.120
Georgia Stitt, S - t - i
- t - t. There are a lot

00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:48.110
of sensational performers.

00:26:48.110 --> 00:26:51.760
I think in a lot of ways we've
reached a real golden age in terms

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:55.890
of the performers because
there's so much fluidity.

00:26:55.890 --> 00:26:58.980
When I started, when we did songs
for A New World, it was really hard

00:26:58.980 --> 00:27:01.940
to find that cast, especially
for the $20 we were paying them

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:05.700
but it was really hard you know.

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:09.990
Billy Porter and Andrea were both
people I knew you know, for many,

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:12.250
many years beforehand so they
sort of did it as a favor to me

00:27:12.250 --> 00:27:13.950
and I built the show on them.

00:27:13.950 --> 00:27:18.010
But it was a really hard show
to cast and it would not be hard

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:22.110
to cast it now, because the
vernacular has kind of grown

00:27:22.110 --> 00:27:25.160
into what people are
more used to singing.

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:27.230
And I think that's true
of the musicians also,

00:27:27.230 --> 00:27:29.240
I think with the stuff
I used to write,

00:27:29.240 --> 00:27:30.560
nobody could play it you know.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:33.100
Others are like oh I can do this
and now there's a lot of guys who

00:27:33.100 --> 00:27:36.800
and girls who can get their
fingers around my stuff

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:38.330
and that's very gratifying.

00:27:38.330 --> 00:27:41.860
I don't, I don't it's because
it's necessarily so much ahead

00:27:41.860 --> 00:27:43.160
of my time, but I just think

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:45.410
that the work is kind
of filtered in its way.

